      <text>
        This was her life now.

        The flowers kept shifting colors—yellows when Florence was pleased with a section, creams when focused, occasional oranges when Kira asked questions that disrupted the flow, soft pinks that might have been concern or empathy or digestive processes—who could possibly know.

        Buddy said, "The pale pink suggests compassion. Or potentially flowering readiness. The literature is inconsistent."

        Kira said, "Please stop helping."

        Finally—*finally*—Florence rolled to what looked like a concluding position.

        Florence said, "That completes the core content."

        Her flowers displayed in full cream glory—clearly proud. "Now we'll proceed to the assessment," she added.

        Holloway said, "A brief quiz to ensure comprehension! Standard protocol!"

        Of course there was a quiz.

        Florence produced bark sheets with questions pressed into them—multiple choice, apparently.

        "You'll have twenty minutes," Florence said. "Passing score is seventy percent."

        Kira took the sheets. Scout rolled closer, peering at the questions with what felt like solidarity.

        Question One: When lifting objects over fifteen kilograms, you should:
        A) Bend at the waist and use your back muscles.
        B) Bend at the knees and lift with your legs.
        C) Ask for assistance.
        D) B and C.

        She chose D—that had been covered extensively.

        Question Two: In the event of a facility fire, you should:
        A) Use the elevator to evacuate quickly.
        B) Proceed to the nearest exit calmly.
        C) Return to your workstation for belongings.
        D) Hide in a supply closet.

        B. Obviously—despite there being no elevators, no workstation, and Kira wasn't even sure what qualified as a "supply closet" in living-plant architecture.

        Question Three: If you witness workplace harassment, proper procedure is to:
        A) Ignore it.
        B) Document the incident and report to your supervisor.
        C) Confront the harasser aggressively.
        D) Leave the workplace permanently.

        B. She supposed—document and report, in a theoretical workplace she didn't have, involving colleagues who didn't exist.

        The questions continued: twenty of them, covering every absurd topic from the training.

        Her leg hurt; she wanted water and to lie down.

        ¶

        She wanted this day to end.

        But she answered every question, applying the ridiculous logic she'd just been taught.

        Florence announced, "Time."

        Several fruiting bodies sprouted around the chamber—Holloway reviewing her answers somehow.

        Scout bounced anxiously.

        Kira waited, past exhaustion into a kind of hollow patience.

        Holloway said, "Eighteen correct out of twenty. Ninety percent! Excellent work!"

        Florence's flowers bloomed into brilliant yellow—genuine pleasure.

        Florence said, "Wonderful! You've successfully completed orientation. You're now cleared for medical evaluation!"

        *Finally.*

        Kira stood, ignoring her leg's sharp protest.
      </text>
